{"id":"2203.11346","submitter":"Jason Bramburger","authors":"Jason J. Bramburger and Bjorn Sandstede","title":"Spatially Localized Structures in Lattice Dynamical Systems","comments":"This paper was published in the Journal of Nonlinear Science volume\n  30 in 2020. We wanted to make a preprint available as well","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s00332-019-09584-x","report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate stationary, spatially localized patterns in lattice dynamical\nsystems that exhibit bistability. The profiles associated with these patterns\nhave a long plateau where the pattern resembles one of the bistable states,\nwhile the profile is close to the second bistable state outside this plateau.\nWe show that the existence branches of such patterns generically form either an\ninfinite stack of closed loops (isolas) or intertwined s-shaped curves\n(snaking). We then use bifurcation theory near the anti-continuum limit, where\nthe coupling between edges in the lattice vanishes, to prove existence of\nisolas and snaking in a bistable discrete real Ginzburg--Landau equation. We\nalso provide numerical evidence for the existence of snaking diagrams for\nplanar localized patches on square and hexagonal lattices and outline a\nstrategy to analyse them rigorously.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 21 Mar 2022 21:17:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-23"}
